CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:c31"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:ccrm"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">I/BNK I/IAV M/FCL N/DJN N/ENTR N/MRK N/POV N/WER N/WLA R/CA R/NME R/US R/USW </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">NWREGULAR WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday SB119038352400065136594045841175302778758041 Bragar, Sandi SYND CODES_REVIEWED Wires Wealth Management </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Markets</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Helping High-Net-Worth Clients Navigate the Challenges of Their Wealth; From managing security to raising children, a trusted adviser can be invaluable to the newly wealthy</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Sandi Bragar</Para><Para>• Managing director in planning strategy and research, principal at Aspiriant, San Francisco • Education: B.A., University of California, Santa Barbara • Professional designations: Certified Public Accountant, Certified Financial Planner</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Background: Ms. Bragar discovered financial planning as a career path in college and was drawn to the field. Growing up, her dad was an entrepreneur, and she witnessed the ups and downs of life with a variable income. "Things were either really flush and exciting—or they weren't," she says. After college, she worked as a tax adviser before deciding to pivot to a career in wealth management.</Para><Para>Her practice: Aspiriant manages $11 billion in assets, serving about 1,600 clients throughout the U.S. Ms. Bragar works with high-net-worth clients, most of whom have accumulated their wealth through lucrative careers as corporate executives or entrepreneurs.</Para><Para>On the unforeseen challenges of wealth: While wealth comes with obvious advantages, financial abundance can also create complexity, says Ms. Bragar. Her firm helps high-profile clients navigate issues such as privacy when purchasing a home, occasionally advising clients to set up an LLC for the transaction. Home security is another common concern among high-net-worth clients, especially those who travel frequently. For high-profile clients, Ms.Bragar recommends consulting with a security firm. She also suggests clients consider using P.O. boxes for mail, freezing their credit and making sure their children are discreet about posting vacation photos in order to avoid broadcasting a vacant home to thieves.</Para><Para>On raising children in a wealthy household: Since many of Ms. Bragar's clients come from modest backgrounds, helping them approach the topic of wealth with their children can be challenging. "A lot of clients who're starting families are concerned about raising children who'll become self-sufficient adults," she says. She notes that some families choose to avoid discussing their financial situation with their children. But others are more open about the family's wealth and the responsibility that comes with it. "It's in these cases that the children know they're expected to be stewards," the adviser says.</Para><Para>On the biggest industry challenge: Ms. Bragar says that the financial services industry needs to do a better job at embracing diversity. "Clients have diverse needs, perspectives and backgrounds. In my experience, clients benefit from a team comprised of different gender, racial and/or religious backgrounds," she says.</Para><Para>On 529s and the tax bill: Many of Ms. Bragar's clients have asked her whether they should take advantage of the new option for funding 529 plans to pay for their children's private K-12 schooling. She's usually in favor of the idea, but notes that some states, such as California, haven't yet conformed to the federal tax rules, which could mean 529 distributions for K-12 tuition would be taxable.</Para><Para>On Machu Picchu and advising: Though she admits to being a reluctant camper, Ms. Bragar hiked Machu Picchu with friends several years ago. She says completing the hike was a significant personal achievement, and offered some parallels to her career as an adviser. "I'd finally reach a peak—and then I'd see all the other peaks. With advising, there are always new peaks to reach, new places to go. Even after 19 years, there's still so much more to learn and discover, and that's really exciting," she says.</Para><Para>Compiled by Lynn Shattuck</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field"></Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/helping-high-net-worth-clients-navigate-the-challenges-of-their-wealth-1522249201" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

